    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1841_11_14_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline> <note>(107)</note>
                        <note>3</note>
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</placeName>
                        <date when="1824-07-06">July 6.<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>1824</date></dateline>
                    <salute>
                        My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">Sir Walter Scott</persName>,
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <p>
                     
                    The enclosed specimen<lb/>
                    of Irish vituperation is<lb/>
                    warranted genuine<lb/>
                    by the gentleman who<lb/>
                    gave it to me - He declares<lb/>
                    that he wrote it down word<lb/>
                    word for word as he heard<lb/>
                    it and I declare that I <choice><orig>be-<lb/>
                    lieve</orig><reg>believe</reg></choice> he could not have<lb/>
                    altered it if he would - and<lb/>
                    that he would not if he<lb/>
                    could - There are "some<lb/>
                    "things I think I could<lb/>
                    "have made better" - But<lb/>
                    even in my infinite conceit<lb/>
                    I respect the truth of <choice><orig>Na<lb/> 
                    ture</orig><reg>Nature</reg></choice> &amp; leave it all to<lb/>
                    your Honor's honor-<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    I doubted whether<lb/>
                    Paddy's land was a <choice><orig>ge<lb/>
                    nuine</orig><reg>genuine</reg></choice> expression, not<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_3899_1824_07_06_page02.jpg"/>
                    having happened to hear<lb/>
                    it in our parts - &amp; I could<lb/>
                    have wished to have<lb/>
                    substituted - the <hi rend="underline"><unclear></unclear>King</hi><lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">doms</hi> - or the <hi rend="underline">United</hi><lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">Kingdom</hi> - or <hi rend="underline">dear little</hi><lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">Dublin</hi> - or in the last<lb/>
                    <del></del>extreme <hi rend="underline">Dunleary</hi><lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">- itself!</hi>- which according<lb/>
                    to my notions would<lb/>
                    have sounded more<lb/>
                    natural - But upon<lb/>
                    strict inquiry - (and I<lb/>
                    have not <hi rend="underline">spared diligence</hi><lb/>
                    as <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JohnS1">D.<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Johnson</persName> would boast)<lb/>
                    I have satisfied myself<lb/>
                    that Paddy's Land is the<lb/>
                    true reading - or the true<lb/>
                    speaking - and I have<lb/>
                    restored the original - <choice><orig>sub<lb/>
                    mitting</orig><reg>submitting</reg></choice> contrary to my<lb/>
                    Irish nature to a Scottish<lb/>
                    proverb -<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">Let well alone</hi> - A proverb<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_3899_1824_07_06_page03.jpg"/>
                    <note>4</note>4
                    I first heard from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BailJ1">Joanna<lb/>
                    Baillie</persName> -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    I have just been reading<lb/>
                    Reginald Dalton for<lb/>
                    the second time - with<lb/>
                    very great pleasure - to<lb/>
                    some friends to whom<lb/>
                    it was new <add>The story of this novel is so constructed that</add>- The <choice><orig>charac<lb/>
                    ter</orig><reg>character</reg></choice> of Macdonald the<lb/>
                    father is admirable - There<lb/>
                    <add>just</add> is a depth of knowledge<lb/>
                    of human nature and<lb/>
                    exquisite humor - The<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockJ1">author</persName> probably would<lb/>
                    shrink &amp; writhe at the<lb/>
                    idea of trusting it to the<lb/>
                    reading of an Irish woman<lb/>
                    but give my services to<lb/>
                    him and assure him<lb/>
                    that My Macdonald<lb/>
                    was heard with <choice><orig>unbound<lb/>
                    ed</orig><reg>unbounded</reg></choice> applause - Like Irish<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MackC1">Macklin</persName> of yore I ruled<lb/>
                    (not swore) that it <hi rend="underline">should</hi><lb/>
                    be Scotch, whatever it was<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    There was <add>in the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockJ1">author</persName> of Reg Dalton</add> great boldness<lb/>
                    curiosity is kept up &amp; baffled till the last<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_3899_1824_07_06_page04.jpg"/>
                    - the boldness of a mind <choice><orig>se<lb/>
                    cure</orig><reg>secure</reg></choice> of original genius, in<lb/>
                    daring this character after<lb/>
                    Sir Pertinax McSycophant<lb/>
                    - It recalls Sir Partinax <hi rend="underline">only</hi><lb/>
                    by the excellence of the<lb/>
                    drawing of the master<lb/>
                    strokes, while it is open <choice><orig>essential<lb/>
                    ly</orig><reg>essentially</reg></choice> different, &amp; a perfectly<lb/>
                    new character - It is in beautiful &amp;<lb/>
                    natural contrast with the amiable vicar-<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    Tell me how your dear<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockS1">Sophia</persName> does and little<lb/>
                    Johnny - our <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeS1">Sophy</persName> is<lb/>
                    now at Cheltenham with<lb/>
                    her beloved &amp; has her sister<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> with her - in<lb/>
                    a pretty cottage trellised<lb/>
                    with roses which she writes<lb/>
                    me word puts her in mind<lb/>
                    of Chiefs Wood - her words are<lb/>
                    "How little I thought when<lb/>
                    "I was at dear Chiefs Wood<lb/>
                    "last year that I should<lb/>
                    "myself so soon be enjoying<lb/>
                    the same sort of happiness<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    Pray write &amp; tell me how<lb/>
                    you are all going on - I have<lb/>
                    had a great loss since I wrote<lb/>
                    to you last - my sister <unclear>Bedo</unclear><lb/>
          
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
        <back> </back>
    </text>
